The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Nation at a Glance

 Patriot purse and MP pension

 New Delhi: From Indias first war of Independence to the adoption of Vande Mataram as national song the government has decided to celebrate a series of events from the freedom struggle.

 The Centre on Thursday set up a Rs 150-crore fund for various anniversary celebrations that will begin with the 150th anniversary of the 1857 revolt in May 2007 and will continue till August 2008.

 In August 2007, the 60th anniversary of Independence will be celebrated. It will be a yearlong affair. The controversial centenary celebration of the adoption of the Vande Mataram as national song and the observance of the 75th martyrdom anniversary and the birth centenary of Shaheed Bhagat Singh are already under way. 

 In another decision, the cabinet has approved the increase in salaries, allowances and pensions under the MP Act. The legislation, already passed by Parliament, will increase the pension for MPs to Rs 8,000 per month from Rs 6,000. 

 Officials said the increased pension bill would cost the exchequer Rs 7 crore per year. 

 The salaries and allowances of MPs have already been enhanced from Rs 12,000 to Rs 16,000 per month. The constituency allowance has been doubled from Rs 10,000 to Rs 20,000 and the daily allowance from Rs 500 to Rs 1,000. 

 Jail relief

 Kochi (PTI): Kerala High Court has directed 

 the state government to immediately release all undertrials 

 who have been lodged in prison for more than the maximum 

 period of punishment for the offences they have been accused 

 of.

 The order was issued by Chief Justice V.K. Bali and Justice P.R. Raman on Thursday.

 Blasts arrest

 Mumbai: The anti-terrorist squad has 

 arrested Shabbir Ahmed Masiullah Ansari alias Shabbir Batterywala 

 in the September 8 Malegaon blasts case, taking the total 

 number of arrests to two. The blasts claimed 31 lives.

 Hair sack stay

 Udaipur (PTI): A tribunal in Jaipur 

 has stayed the dismissal of five teachers of a private school 

 in Udaipur after they allegedly cut the hair of 50 students 

 two days ago. The five were arrested on Tuesday following 

 a complaint lodged by a student. 

 A 700-year-old imambara in Srinagar will be renovated at a cost 

 of Rs 9 crore, Jammu and Kashmir tourism minister Mohammad 

 Dilawar Mir has said.




